(including salaries, benefits, and share-based compensation), power generation costs, and depreciation of data center assets, including processors, equipment lease expenses, and networking equipment."*\n\nFor FY 2025, total AI R&D was **$5,064M**, comprising:\n\n| Component | Estimated FY 2025 |\n|---|---|\n| GPU depreciation | ~$1,673M (incremental) + base ≈ **$1,800M+** |\n| Cloud computing & data center infrastructure | ~$1,440M (incremental) + base ≈ **$1,600M+** |\n| Employee compensation + overhead | ~$775M (incremental) + base ≈ **$900M+** |\n| Power, leases, other | Remainder |\n\n*(These are rough approximations by summing incremental changes to prior year base of $1,176M)*\n\n---\n\n## What Is **Not** Separately Disclosed\n\nThe documents do **not** provide:\n\n1. **A standalone "GPU procurement cost" line item** — GPU purchases are buried within total AI CapEx alongside data center construction, networking, and facilities.\n\n2. **The 30/70 split applied to this company\'s own CapEx** — The SemiAnalysis industry benchmark (30% data center construction, 70% processors/equipment) is cited as general industry data, **not** as this company\'s own ratio.\n\n3. **Cloud computing costs broken out between third-party cloud (e.g., AWS/GCP/Azure) vs. owned data center operating costs** — Both are lumped together.\n\n4. **A clear CapEx-to-depreciation reconciliation** — While you can see CapEx of $5,633M in FY2024 and total AI D&A of $1,679M in FY2025, the documents don\'t provide a PP&E rollforward specific to the AI segment or the useful life assumptions for GPUs.\n\n5. **Power costs separately** — Listed as a component of R&D but never quantified independently.\n\n---\n\n## How Compute Costs Are Treated: Capitalized vs. Expensed\n\nThe accounting treatment follows this framework:\n\n```\nCAPITALIZED (Balance Sheet → CapEx)\n├── GPU hardware procurement\n├── Servers and networking equipment\n├── Data center construction (shell, MEP, power)\n├── Construction-in-progress (not yet in service)\n└── Capitalized interest during construction\n\nEXPENSED (P&L — R&D)\n├── GPU depreciation (once placed in service)\n├── Cloud computing expenses (third-party)\n├── Power/energy costs to run processors\n├── Equipment lease expenses\n└── Employee compensation for AI R&D\n\nEXPENSED (P&L — Cost of Revenue)\n└── Infrastructure and cloud computing costs\n    related to delivering AI products/services\n```\n\n---\n\n## The Key Insight: Segmented Economics\n\nThe supplemental segment tables reveal the dramatic scaling:\n\n| Metric | AI Segment 2023 | AI Segment 2024 | AI Segment Q1 2025 | AI Segment Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Revenue | $2,961M | $2,620M | $727M | ~$818M* |\n| CapEx | $463M | $5,633M | $2,567M | Not disclosed |\n| D&A | $1,180M | $1,679M | $771M | Not disclosed |\n| R&D | $186M | $1,176M | $908M | $2,379M |\n| Op Loss | $(3,973M) | $(1,561M) | $(936M) | $(2,469M) |\n\n*Revenue estimated from the $91M YoY increase cited in the MD&A.\n\nThe trajectory shows CapEx **accelerating far ahead of depreciation**, meaning a growing base of compute assets is being built but hasn\'t yet fully flowed through to the P&L. As these assets depreciate (typically over 3-5 years for server hardware), the depreciation component of R&D will continue climbing — a significant headwind the company warns will persist for a **"multi-year investment horizon"** before reaching sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA.',
