 3. Cloud Computing Costs vs. Owned Infrastructure Costs\nThe disclosures indicate the company uses a **hybrid model of both third-party cloud computing and owned infrastructure**, but a precise ratio is **not explicitly provided**.\n\n*   **Cloud Computing:** The MD&A consistently lists **"cloud computing expenses"** as a component of AI segment R&D and cost of revenue. This represents ongoing operational costs for renting compute capacity from third-party providers.\n*   **Owned Infrastructure:** The massive and growing balances in **"Servers and networking equipment"** ($23.9B as of March 2026) and **"Construction-in-progress"** ($14.0B as of March 2026, primarily for AI infrastructure) signify heavy investment in owned hardware and data centers. The capitalized interest disclosure reinforces this.\n*   **Conclusion:** The financial statements clearly show the company is both spending on **cloud computing services (OpEx)** and making **substantial capital expenditures (CapEx)** to build out its own infrastructure. The text does not break down the ratio between the two, but the scale of CapEx suggests a strategic focus on controlling long-term compute costs through owned assets.\n\n**In summary:** For the AI segment, the disclosed capital expenditures align with a ~70/30 hardware-to-construction split, GPU assets have a 5-6 year useful life, and the company employs a hybrid compute strategy involving both cloud services and significant owned infrastructure investment.',
