of COLOSSUS (122 days) and COLOSSUS II (91 days) compared to an industry benchmark of **~2 years** for a 100MW greenfield data center as proof of its speed and cost advantage.\n*   **Expense Drivers:** Financial statements confirm the dual cost drivers.\n    *   **GPU/Hardware Costs:** Highlighted as a major expense. Research & Development expense for the AI segment increased by **$1,471 million** in Q1 2026, driven primarily by **"depreciation of GPU hardware."**\n    *   **Data Center Construction Costs:** Disclosed as "construction-in-progress" for "AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service." Depreciation of these assets is a significant and growing line item (e.g., **$5,915 million** for 2025).\n*   **Vertical Integration Strategy:** The filing positions the company\'s vertical integration (e.g., the **Terafab** initiative with Tesla to manufacture compute hardware) as a direct strategy to reduce future "compute hardware costs" and alleviate supply chain issues. This indicates a focus on controlling the 70% cost component identified in the benchmark.\n\n### Summary\n| Disclosure Type | Content | Source/Context |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Industry Benchmark** | **70% processors/IT, 30% data center construction** | Cited as an **industry-wide figure** from SemiAnalysis in the Preamble. |\n| **Company-Specific** | **Costs are "considerably lower" per MW** than industry benchmarks. | **Preamble:** Claimed competitive advantage for COLOSSUS II. |\n| **Company-Specific** | **Dual Cost Drivers:** Significant expenses for **GPU depreciation** and **data center construction-in-progress.** | **MD&A & Financial Statements:** Describes the primary components of AI segment losses and capital intensity. |\n| **Company-Specific** | **Vertical Integration (Terafab)** aims to reduce **compute hardware costs.** | **Preamble:** Strategy to control a major portion of the cost structure. |\n\n**Conclusion:** The 70/30 split is presented as a **general industry benchmark**. The company does not provide its own specific percentage ratio but demonstrates through operational claims (speed, cost per MW) and financial disclosures (massive depreciation of GPUs and construction-in-progress) that it is aggressively managing both sides of this cost equation, with a particular strategic emphasis on controlling hardware costs through vertical integration.',
